<br>
There is a VERY common misconception about love, namely that it is this feeling that should constantly tickle your senses and fill your stomach with butterflies.<br>
<br>
Love is a choice, not merely a feeling.<br>
<br>
When your child does something annoying or frustrating, the emotion(s) of anger and/or frustration might surge up and overwhelm the &quot;emotional&quot; feeling of love.  That is where you must choose to love your child and conduct yourself appropriately.<br>
<br>
This is the same for a spouse/partner.  After &quot;a while&quot;, everyone becomes human and &quot;less fascinating&quot;.  Likewise the level of comfort that develops between people over time diminishes the necessity for &quot;finding something interesting to talk about&quot; or trying to impress someone.  Accordingly, you will almost always find someone who is &quot;more attractive&quot; or &quot;more interesting&quot; or &quot;more stimulating&quot; than your spouse.  Always.  That's just the way human brains work.  The mythological state of being where you &quot;only have eyes for your spouse&quot; is exactly that, a myth.  <br>
<br>
People interact and in the process of interacting there are a number of fairly predictable responses, and feeling attraction to another person is merely part of that process.  However feeling attraction and conciously acting upon it are two entirely different things.<br>
<br>
While there are physiological and neurological unconcious behaviors associated with &quot;love&quot;, the most important are the concious behaviors that true love requires.  It is difficult to accept this truth about love, because it requires work and requires a person to suppress desires that might feel &quot;right&quot; or &quot;natural&quot;.  However if you follow those desires to their most likely conclusion, pursuing those feelings with someone who is not your spouse, is an act of choosing not to love your spouse.<br>
<br>
Now, you can either accept or object my arguement above, however the simplest way of understanding how this behavior is a clear act of choosing not to love someone who you've pledged vows to, is to consider how you would feel if you came to know that your husband has had feelings for, and pursued these feelings with, another woman.<br>
<br>
So in short, choose to love your spouse and talk with him about what you feel is missing.  Anything less is a disservice to your husband, yourself, and the concept of marriage.<br>
